`categoryOf()` does `categories.find(...)` — O(n) — and gets called once per book, inside loops, on every render/search:

```ts
// src/lib/content.ts
export function categoryOf(book: Book): Category | undefined {
  return categories.find((c) => c.id === book.categoryId)   // called per-book, per-render
}
```
`searchBooks()` calls it inside `.map()` over every book, on every keystroke. A `catOrder` Map already exists for sort order — add a sibling Map for lookup:

```ts
const categoriesById = new Map(categories.map((c) => [c.id, c]))
export function categoryOf(book: Book): Category | undefined {
  return categoriesById.get(book.categoryId)
}
```

**Biggest issue** — `BookCard` in `Library.tsx` subscribes to the *entire* progress store per card:

```tsx
function BookCard({ book, step }: { book: Book; step?: number }) {
  const all = useAllProgress()          // ← whole store
  const progress = all[book.id]
  ...
```

`useStore`/`useSyncExternalStore` has no selector — it re-renders on *any* state change. Result: marking one chapter read in one book re-renders **every** `BookCard` on the page, not just the affected one. `progress.ts` already has a scoped `useBookProgress(bookId)` (used correctly in `BookMap.tsx`/`Reader.tsx`) — use it here too:

```tsx
function BookCard({ book, step }: { book: Book; step?: number }) {
  const progress = useBookProgress(book.id)   // still whole-store subscribe, but consistent + sanitized
```

That alone fixes a latent bug (raw `all[book.id]` skips `sanitize()`, so a malformed localStorage entry could crash `completionPct`). For the deeper fix — actually scoping re-renders per book — `store.ts`'s `useStore` needs a selector variant with cached-snapshot equality (otherwise `useSyncExternalStore` still re-renders since a new object is returned each call):

```ts
// store.ts
export function useStoreSelector<T extends object, S>(
  store: Store<T>,
  selector: (s: T) => S,
  equal: (a: S, b: S) => boolean = Object.is,
): S {
  const cache = useRef<S>()
  const getSnapshot = () => {
    const next = selector(store.get())
    if (cache.current === undefined || !equal(cache.current, next)) cache.current = next
    return cache.current
  }
  return useSyncExternalStore(store.subscribe, getSnapshot, getSnapshot)
}
```
Then `useBookProgress` becomes truly scoped, and a progress update to Book A no longer re-renders Book B/C/D's cards. Worth doing once the library grows past a handful of books.

**`bookStats(book)`** re-derives word counts (regex splits over every chapter summary) on *every call* — and it's called per `BookCard`, in `ContinueStrip`, in `BookMap`, and in `Library`'s totals. Since `books` are static module-level data, this never changes at runtime — cache it once:

```ts
// content.ts
const statsCache = new Map<string, BookStats>()
export function bookStats(b: Book): BookStats {
  const cached = statsCache.get(b.id)
  if (cached) return cached
  const stats = computeBookStats(b)   // existing logic, renamed
  statsCache.set(b.id, stats)
  return stats
}
```

**`loadChapter`** re-fetches and re-parses markdown (via `marked`) every time a chapter is opened, even if the user already visited it this session (e.g., navigating back via browser or reopening from the map):

```ts
// content.ts
const chapterCache = new Map<string, Chapter>()
export async function loadChapter(bookId: string, n: number): Promise<Chapter | null> {
  const key = `${bookId}#${n}`
  const cached = chapterCache.get(key)
  if (cached) return cached
  const loader = chapterIndex.get(bookId)?.get(n)
  if (!loader) return null
  const raw = await loader()
  // ...existing parsing...
  chapterCache.set(key, chapter)
  return chapter
}
```
This also avoids double-parsing when React StrictMode double-invokes effects in dev.

